message: Wishing you and yours a very happy New Year!
This week, our unified Republican Congress hits the ground running to restore the people’s voice in representative government.
It was a blessing to have my family with me today as I was sworn into the 115th Congress. I’m deeply honored to continue to serve the people of Eastern Washington in the People’s House.

Honored to have Vice President-elect Mike Pence join us today to talk about the upcoming year. I’m ready and excited for us to hit the ground running and work on the issues important to the people of Eastern Washington and the country.

The very first bill passed by our new Congress will work to bring accountability to the VA and help ensure our veterans get quality care. Happy to support the Ensuring VA Employee Accountability Act so that we have the best and most qualified employees taking care of our nation’s heroes.   http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/house-votes-to-end-va-scrubbing-of-employee-records/article/2610806
Honored to join my colleagues on the House floor today to read the Constitution. Here’s me reading my section.

In the final days of his presidency, President Obama and his administration have passed sweeping, burdensome rules and regulations that only solidify his legacy as a president who governs by executive overreach. This is unacceptable, and this week, the People’s House took action. We passed the Midnight Rules Relief Act, which gives Congress the power to review and stop all major rules finalized 60 legislative days before Congress recessed. This means we have the ability to review every rule and regulation President Obama’s administration has issued since the middle of May. Currently under the Congressional Review Act, Congress can only stop regulations one at a time. This bill allows Congress to stop multiple regulations at once and faster respond to the regulatory onslaught from the administration. Americans were loud and clear on November 8: people are sick and tired of being governed from the top-down. President Obama has made life harder for Americans by passing burdensome regulations that increase the cost of living and interfere with everyday life. His regulations stifle innovation, hurt businesses, and especially for those in Eastern Washington, make farming difficult for American families. Executive overreach is not how America was founded, and the Midnight Rules Relief Act stops President Obama’s legacy of overregulation in its tracks.   http://www.wsj.com/articles/obamas-midnight-regulation-express-1482451192

Today and every day, we owe a debt of gratitude to our nation’s law enforcement officers, who put themselves in harm’s way to serve and protect. Like my friend Congressman Dave Reichert, a former Sheriff, often says, for our officers there is no off duty. They have a difficult, often impossible, job and it often is thankless as well. I’m grateful for the sheriffs and officers in Eastern Washington, the Capitol Police, and the men and women across the country who put on the uniform and do right by their communities. #LEappreciationday
Spending time outdoors is a big part of life in the Northwest. I’m happy to see the Outdoor Rec Act signed into law.    http://www.sunherald.com/sports/outdoors/article125228164.html

I’ve been thinking a lot about the farewell address President Obama gave last night. His speech reminds me of the stories I hear from people across Eastern Washington who are being crushed by all of the rules and regulations that came out of his presidency. You may be asking yourself, what does all of this talk about “rules and regulations” actually mean?  Well, for the local business owner or family, it means unnecessary, expensive, jobs-crushing mandates, and it’s a big reason why our economy isn’t doing as well as it could be.   This is why I’m so pleased to see House Republicans kicking off the year by undoing and reining in the most harmful aspects of President Obama’s legacy: burdensome rules and regulations. It’s an important step we’re taking to set the table for our unified Republican government to make real progress for people.

Obamacare was the federal government’s best effort to ‘fix’ our health care system, and it failed. This week, we’re fulfilling our promise to take the first steps towards repealing it. This is about developing a long-term solution that works for everyone, and I believe everyone deserves access to affordable, quality health care coverage. You, not the government, should be in control of your own health care.   https://mcmorris.house.gov/mcmorris-rodgers-statement-house-passing-obamacare-repeal-resolution/

Since 2014, over 500 cases of human trafficking have been investigated in our four state area. Yesterday in Spokane, my staff attended a human trafficking candlelight vigil hosted by Lutheran Community Services, Partners Through Art, and Generation Alive to help raise awareness.
You don't win them all. These little Seahawks fans still enjoyed watching yesterday! #GoHawks

Martin Luther King Jr. Day is a moment for us to reflect on a man who changed the course of history. He took it upon himself to be the example for us all and lived the values he wanted to see in the world. His courage and peaceful legacy is one that has been on my heart, especially coming out of such a tense election cycle, and the word I keep coming back to is “unity.” How do we, as a nation, come together and heal?  Every man, woman, and child in this country should be treated with dignity and respect, no matter their background or walk of life. More needs to be done to address racial division in America, and I believe that starts with finding fundamental values that unite us all. We need to continue to challenge ourselves to do the hard work of bringing everyone to the table, especially those with whom we disagree, because I believe peaceful disagreement and discussion is fundamental to finding common ground.
Sad to see the #Eags lose Coach Beau Baldwin, but happy for him in his new career. Wishing him all the best!

I always love getting to talk with young people in our community. Today I was able to stop by Centennial Middle School in Spokane Valley! They just finished learning about the founding of the United States and I was able to talk more about our Constitution and the important balance of powers that our Founding Fathers envisioned for our country.

Yesterday, I was honored to join the Spokane NAACP for a roundtable discussion on how we can come together as a community to work towards change and progress. More needs to be done to address racial division in America, and I believe that although we all come from different backgrounds, cultures, and races, we are all united in our goal to make our community stronger, safer, and more prosperous for everyone. I am especially thankful for Phil Tyler, the new president of the Spokane NAACP, who is willing to do the hard work of bringing everyone to the table to focus on the core beliefs that unite us all.  https://mcmorris.house.gov/mcmorris-rodgers-joins-spokane-naacp-peaceful-communities-roundtable/

It’s great seeing so many people from Eastern Washington in town for the Inauguration! I'm glad so many people from our area could join.

I’m headed over to the #Inauguration2017 right now with my husband, Brian, and look forward to seeing President-elect Trump take the Oath of Office in less than two hours from now to become the 45th President of the United States. The significance of this historic moment, regardless of your political beliefs, is one that sets America apart from the rest of the world. The peaceful transfer of power is something to celebrate and cherish-- a freedom that we, as Americans, have been blessed with since America’s founding. God bless America on today and all days as we start this new chapter in our nation’s history.   Follow the livestream of the Inauguration here: https://www.inaugural.senate.gov/

It’s an exciting time in our nation’s capital. An Inauguration is a time of new beginnings. It brings with it hope of a better tomorrow for everyone in this country. We cherish the peaceful transfer of power. Today means a fresh start and an opportunity to make a meaningful impact on people’s lives. We have new leadership and a unified Republican government. This moment is a call from the American people -- it’s time to be legendary, to think big, and to reimagine government. It’s time to put the voice of every man, woman, and child in this country back where it belongs: at the core of our representative government.  I look forward to working with President Trump and Vice President Pence to offer relief to workers and families across this country. This is the positive disruption Americans have been waiting for, and now we’re ready to make America great again.  https://mcmorris.house.gov/mcmorris-rodgers-statement-inauguration-president-donald-j-trump/

Today, Jaime Herrera Beutler, Rep. Dan Newhouse, and Congressman Dave Reichert and I responded to Governor Inslee’s letter about the future of health care. We firmly believe that everyone, including individuals with pre-existing conditions, should have access to health care coverage. That coverage should protect the sanctity of the patient-doctor relationship; provide choice because one-size does not fit all; and most importantly be affordable. While Americans that were previously uninsured may now have health care coverage, it means nothing if they cannot afford to use it – and the numbers show that today’s health insurance is woefully unaffordable.   Individuals and their families deserve health care reform that is done thoughtfully and responsibly with a smooth transition, and no one should have the rug pulled out from underneath them. Therefore, as we repeal the ACA we are also diligently working with local stakeholders, health care experts, Members of Congress on both sides of the aisle, and the Administration to enact long-term, 21st century solutions that give people access to affordable, quality health care coverage focused on personalized, patient-centered care. It’s time to put Americans back in control of their health care decisions.  https://mcmorris.house.gov/wa-gop-delegation-sends-letter-governor-inslee-commissioner-mike-kreidler/

House and Senate Republicans are in Philadelphia this week for our joint retreat, and earlier today I kicked off our first of three days discussing policy solutions that create jobs and grow our economy. Over the next few days we’ll be hearing from a variety of speakers and holding policy sessions that focus on improving our tax code, reining in government regulations, strengthening our national security, and restoring people’s control over their own health care. This is a moment we’ve been given-- a moment to think big and advance conservative policies-- and our retreat is about charting the course for the next 200 days on how to best put our plans in motion as a unified Republican government.

This week is #SchoolChoice Week across the country, and as a mom of three--one of whom has special needs--I am thankful to have options when it comes to choosing how to best meet my kids’ educational needs. I want every parent and every child to be able to choose the best educational system for them, because when it comes to education, one size does not fit all. Our little learners benefit from different styles -- whether that’s a brick-and-mortar school or a digital one-- and let’s not forget about our homeschoolers! Educational choice is about the freedom to choose the best way to meet your child’s educational needs. It’s about trusting parents or guardians to make the best educational decisions for their children, and it’s about providing options to our little learners so that we are preparing them for college and career readiness. At the end of the day, school choice is about ensuring our next generation is set up for success.

Obamacare has not fulfilled the promises it made to the American people. It’s raised out-of-pocket costs, premiums, and deductibles; choices have gone down to where some only have one option on exchanges; and people have had to change insurance coverage or doctors. We need a new way for people to have access to quality care; 21st Century health care that works for everyone. I’m committed to protecting those with pre-existing conditions and allowing young people to stay on their parents insurance until age 26. And I will work to make sure these are included in our replacement plan, because 21st Century health care doesn’t pick winners or losers, it makes sure that everyone, no matter your background or walk of life, has access to quality and affordable health care. Happy to see my committee, the House Committee on Energy and Commerce, lead on introducing legislation to ensure these important provisions are included in our plan.   https://energycommerce.house.gov/news-center/news/walden-set-introduce-bill-protecting-patients-pre-existing-conditions

Today’s annual National Prayer Breakfast in Washington, D.C., serves as a reminder that, no matter who we are, no matter what we believe in, we can all come together and find common ground. There's a lot of anger and emotion right now, and if there ever were a time when we need to be dedicating ourselves to prayer, it's now. I believe in the power of prayer, and I’m praying that we as Americans can find peace and unity as we work together to solve the troubles that weigh so heavily on our hearts and our country.

We must remember that although we come from different backgrounds and ideologies, we’re all part of this great experiment in self-governance. We’re all united by common values of liberty, justice and equality of opportunity, even if we don’t always agree on how to achieve them. This message is so important now, more than ever. Here you can read my op-ed on how we can come together and bridge the political divide.

A few weeks ago, I invited Spokane Army Major Scotty Smiley to speak at the Republican Retreat about his vision of “service before self.” Scotty and his wife, Tiffany, have an amazing story about overcoming insurmountable odds to make a difference in the world. What some may not know is that Scotty and Tiffany are vocal advocates for reforming the VA. In 2005, Scotty was blinded by a suicide bomber in Iraq, and as he was learning to live with his blindness, he experienced firsthand how VA bureaucracy stands in the way of our veterans getting the care and resources they need to live a full life. Our veterans put their lives on the line for our country, and as a grateful nation, we need to hold the VA accountable for its culture problem and for consistently failing to put our veterans first. Thank you to Scotty Smiley and Tiffany Smiley for spreading the word. It’s time to reform the VA so that the red carpet is rolled out for our veterans every single time they walk through the door.

Yesterday and today, all of my Eastern Washington and D.C.-based staff met here in D.C. for our annual all-staff working session. It’s a time for us all to strategize on policy, share ideas, and discuss how we best deliver results to everyone in Eastern Washington. Something I’ve especially been focused on is how to change the culture in our government. I believe changing the culture starts with us, and our office adopted a system of values, called SERVE, that guides us in all we do. The office motto is, “Have Fun While We SERVE,” and SERVE stands for: Seek Excellence...Everybody Matters...Responsibly Own It...Vigilant Integrity...Embrace Change.  I share our value system because I want you to know how important it is to me for everyone to be able to come to the table and share your ideas. Even if we disagree, I think it’s the hallmark of a democracy to be able to discuss and debate ideas in a respectful and thoughtful manner. Hearing from you makes me a better representative, and I am thankful and honored every day to serve everyone in Eastern Washington as your advocate in the People’s House.

I met Grace last month in Spokane, and her love of life is inspiring. Because she’s battling Sickle Cell Anemia, she requires blood transfusions every four weeks for the rest of her life, unless she is able to receive a successful bone marrow transplant, which would cure her disease. Let’s help spread her story so together, as a community, we can help her find a match and change her life. Find out more at bethematch.org.

The Secure Rural Schools program is critical to our rural communities, like those in Northeastern Washington. It provides them with the much-needed revenue to continue providing essential services, fund public education, and maintain their infrastructure. While we work toward active forestry reforms to get our federal forests working again, we must still provide certainty for our counties. I’m proud to help lead this effort because thousands of students, educators, and people in our rural communities rely on this important program.   https://mcmorris.house.gov/mcmorris-rodgers-leads-letter-support-critical-funding-secure-rural-schools-program/

“If you want to travel fast, go alone. If you want to travel far, go together.”   We may not always agree, but we can disagree without being disagreeable with one another. In fact, we can move mountains and come together to find common ground. It was great being in Olympia yesterday to meet with our local legislators and discuss the impact of Obamacare on our state. As we work to repeal Obamacare and replace it with a people-first, 21st Century health care system, I’ve been working in the People’s House to strengthen Medicaid and protections for people with pre-existing conditions so the most vulnerable are covered. Just last week I cosponsored a bill that makes sure people with pre-existing conditions have peace of mind knowing they will have affordable options for health care coverage.

Smart regulations absolutely have their place in government. But the Obama Administration set new records in their creation of this regulatory regime. We can regulate in a way that does not kill jobs and small businesses, and that’s why we’ve worked this year to undo the most harmful aspects of Obama’s presidency: burdensome rules and regulations.

The Pre-Existing Conditions Protection Act, which I’ve co-sponsored, will ensure those with pre-existing conditions have access to health care, and that insurance companies can’t raise rates based on an individual's health.

I enjoyed meeting this week with many folks from our community who were in D.C., like my meeting with the Eastern Washington American Legion to talk about issues facing our veterans. Thanks Mike Bondurant and everyone who joined!

As I said in my interview with Erin Burnett this week, protecting those with pre-existing conditions has long been a priority for me and for other Republicans. In fact, the Republican alternative health care plan offered during the Obamacare debate back in 2009 included protections for those with pre-existing conditions. Pre-existing conditions aren’t the only aspect of Obamacare. Obamacare changed the entire insurance marketplace. It mandated that individuals buy health insurance or face a penalty while also mandating what types of plans they could choose from. It expanded Medicaid, a program that doesn’t provide adequate access to care, and taxed various aspects of care, drastically raising the costs of health care for Americans across the country. As we work to repeal this law, I am committed to getting rid of the harmful and costly aspects of Obamacare and ensuring that people with pre-existing conditions have access to affordable care.

The Regulatory Integrity Act, which passed the House this week, will help make sure situations like “What’s Upstream” never happen again. The EPA’s outrageous “What’s Upstream” campaign in Washington attempted to smear our farmers and ranchers. Washington state, and especially northeastern Washington, depends on the timber industry as a way of life. That’s why today I joined multiple Senators and Representatives, including Rep. Suzan DelBene, my Democrat colleague from Washington’s first district, to introduce the Timber Innovation Act. This legislation is a win for towns like Colville, which benefits from the resources supplied by Colville National Forest. It encourages the use of cross laminated timber (CLT), which will provide new markets for the production of advanced wood buildings throughout Eastern Washington. This is a win for our timber industry and has the added benefit of helping to properly manage our forests so that if and when wildfires do break out, they can be better contained.

We are on a mission to repeal and replace Obamacare. It’s a rescue mission to save families and patients all across this country. And we’re starting this process immediately, in fact, this morning I will be at the House Committee on Energy and Commerce, working through our legislation, the American Health Care Act, in an open, step-by-step process.

We’re on a rescue mission. Obamacare, though well-intentioned, has failed. People in Eastern Washington are paying more and more for health care. Below are my comments during the House Committee on Energy and Commerce markup -- one step in an open, transparent, step-by-step process to repeal Obamacare and replace it with a people-first approach to health care.

We had a break during today’s House Committee on Energy and Commerce markup of the American Health Care Act, so I wanted to take time to answer some of the questions you’ve asked me about our plan to replace Obamacare with people-first health care.

Pleased to have President Donald J. Trump and his Administration backing our plan to rescue people from Obamacare and replace it with a 21st Century health system that puts people first. Here’s HHS Secretary Tom Price, M.D.'s letter of support.
Obamacare failed in its goals and promises. This is our opportunity to bring back choices and competition, and bring down costs of health care.

We just finished our markup of The American Health Care Act in the House Committee on Energy and Commerce. This debate over how we ensure that people have access to quality and affordable health care is a top priority for us.

The Mercatus Center at George Mason University has a detailed study out about how the Congressional Budget Office (CBO) has miscalculated the ACA coverage numbers and what this likely means for the CBO projections for the American Health Care Act. This is about giving people the choice to buy health care insurance rather than forcing them to buy insurance they didn’t want or need.

Safety nets and protections are important, and must be maintained for people who need them the most. There are so many reasons to be concerned by this ruling. First, by spilling more water over the dams, less power will be generated, so Washington residents should expect to see their power bills increase. Secondly, the court ordered all maintenance on our dams to be halted while this year-long environmental study is undertaken, which only further delays the much-needed infrastructure updates to our dams. Thirdly, fish returns have been the highest they’ve been since the dams were built, and this court ruling neglects to take those numbers into account. Fourth, we already spill about 1/3rd of the water that passes through the dams, and increasing the amount is not scientifically based--and likely counterproductive--to fish returns.   There are groups actively advocating to tear down our dams, which I believe is very short-sighted and would cause more harm than good to the environment and to our economy.

A job is so much more than a paycheck. It’s what gives you purpose and dignity. It’s the opportunity for a better life, and that’s what we’re doing with today’s introduction of ABLE 2.0, specifically the ABLE to Work Act. Too often, people with disabilities live in poverty because the current system forces them to make a choice between disability benefits and work. This legislation empowers people with disabilities to save the money they earn from work while remaining eligible for the critical disability safety net. At the end of the day, this is about empowering people with disabilities, like my son Cole, to live their fullest, independent life. Learn more about my legislation here: https://mcmorris.house.gov/able/

Each spring for thousands of years, those of the Jewish faith worldwide have participated in Passover Seders to remember the time when they were slaves in Egypt and to celebrate their deliverance into the land of Israel.   The recent terrorist bombings in Egypt against Coptic Christians reminds us that the Middle East is still torn by ancient hatreds and fears.  Here in America, the familiar story of the Exodus and the ritual meal where the tale is told is especially poignant, where the memory of slavery and anti-Semitism is still fresh. Today the American Jewish Community not only celebrate their ancient freedom, but the one they enjoy every day living in a country where religious freedom is enshrined in the Constitution.  This year has been marred by vandalism at Jewish cemeteries and bomb threats against Jewish community centers.  I co-sponsored bipartisan legislation called the “Combating Anti-Semitism Act,” to make such actions a federal hate crime. But laws alone will not solve the deep divisions in our country.  At a time when Jewish people are gathering for Passover, and Christians preparing for the Easter holiday, I pray we can together remember the verse from Exodus that urges us to treat people different than ourselves with kindness, since “you were once strangers in the land of Egypt.”  I hope that this year, as you enjoy time with family and friends, the biter memory of slavery and persecution will be mixed with the sweet feeling of liberty, knowing that you live in a free country and that Israel is once again the home of the Jewish people.

This morning I met with the Walla Walla Valley Disability Network to talk about local resources and programs for those with disabilities, many of which the group leads, and Medicaid and health care reform. I told the group that I am committed to protecting those with pre-existing conditions, and ensuring Medicaid is protected for those vulnerable populations -- like individuals with disabilities -- who truly need it. I’ve also recently introduced legislation to help those with disabilities save their work income and still remain eligible for disability benefits. The group represented several transport agencies from 4 counties, the CEO of Colville's hospital, county government, and a volunteer fire district. The closing of the Newport Ambulance was a blow to the area, and I’m concerned about the Stevens County Sheriff’s ambulance’s ability to stay open. Our discussion today focused on identifying the root cause of what is causing rural ambulances to suffer, and considering solutions to provide a secure future for ambulances.

I’ve long advocated for better management of our forests, and today’s discussion in Colville focused on management reform, an update on the Colville Forest Plan, and my Timber Innovation Act and how it can help our forests. In the House, I’m part of the Working Forests Caucus and regularly introduce legislation to help us be good stewards of our forests and natural resources. Thanks to those who are a part of the Northeast Washington Forestry Coalition and others. Really good discussion today!

Today, I met with The Arc of Spokane to discuss issues facing people with disabilities and their families. I believe it is fundamental that we have protections for those with pre-existing conditions, and that was a major concern I heard during the meeting. They also shared their thoughts on Medicaid. For too long, billions of dollars in federal programs have continued to receive funding despite their authorizations expiring years or even decades ago. I call these programs “zombies” because they continue on with no end in sight. What’s an authorization? An authorization is the process under which Congress establishes or continues the operation of agencies and programs - and it's a vital part of our job. During the authorization process, Congress provides oversight over all programs, reviews them, rethinks them, or changes them. This is an important part of the legislative process, but it unfortunately has been neglected in recent years.   That’s why today, I introduced the Unauthorized Spending Accountability (USA) Act to make Congress do its job and properly review and rethink federal programs. My legislation targets unauthorized programs and puts them on a pathway to sunset in three years if they're not reauthorized. Learn more about the USA Act here: https://mcmorris.house.gov/usaact/
Great article in the Washington Examiner about my USA Act. I am fighting back against the zombie apocalypse of unauthorized programs threatening to take over our government. #USAAct

The Unauthorized Spending Accountability (USA) Act is crucial to restoring our power of the purse and Congressional oversight over all of your tax dollars. As I told Maria Bartiromo this morning on Fox Business, “Anyone who cares about accountability, should care about unauthorized spending.” You can read more about this legislation here: https://mcmorris.house.gov/usaact/

Last year, $310 billion of your tax dollars went to programs whose authorizations for funding had expired. My Unauthorized Spending Accountability (USA) Act will make Congress do its job in properly going through the authorization process on these programs so we can review, rethink, and possibly eliminate programs that have served their purpose. Beware of these zombies!

For those who enjoy pizza, sandwiches, or food with more than one ingredient, your favorite food place is about to get hit with a new 400-page regulation by the FDA. This FDA regulation, which is set to take effect May 5, has an estimated compliance cost of nearly $1 billion — and that’s just for grocers. Coupled with the predicted 14.5 million hours of paperwork, this is one of the most expensive and onerous regulations of the entire Obama administration.  The FDA regulation puts strict, burdensome regulations on menu labeling in a way that really hits our small business owners hard. Now, don’t get me wrong: I support nutrition information being open and accessible, which is why I’ve introduced bipartisan legislation that still requires menu labeling but also allows for flexibility for restaurants and other retailers, like convenience stores, grocery stores, and pizza delivery stores, in how they provide nutritional information in a way that makes the most sense for their stores and customers. The graphic below shows how tough this regulation is: for a sandwich shop that offers 30 toppings, they’d have to print or write the nutrition information for around 30 million different combinations of sandwiches. Imagine how much paper that would take to print a menu that long! I think that nutrition information should be provided in a way that uses 21st century technology so that the cost to our small mom and pop shops and convenience stores doesn’t put them out of business. Imagine being forced to write 30 million different combinations of sandwiches on your chalkboard behind your counter! That’s time-consuming, burdensome, and for many, unachievable. That’s why my legislation brings back common sense to menu labeling. Learn more here: https://mcmorris.house.gov/common-sense-menu-labeling/

Protecting people with pre-existing conditions is a priority of mine. As we prepare to vote on the American Health Care Act (AHCA) tomorrow, I want you to know that I'm a co-sponsor of the latest amendment, which dedicates $8 billion to reduce premiums and other out-of-pocket costs for patients in the individual market with pre-existing conditions. The AHCA would allow waivers to states if they meet very specific standards, including the standard that premiums for individuals living with pre-existing conditions must be stabilized, meaning premiums cannot be unaffordable. At no time is any insurance company permitted to deny access to coverage for people with pre-existing conditions. If a state applies for a waiver and you have a pre-existing condition and don’t have continuous health care coverage, the $8 billion fund helps lower premium costs. To me, protecting people with pre-existing conditions isn’t just good policy: it’s a personal mission. That’s why I’m a co-sponsor of this amendment and have fought to make sure everyone with pre-existing conditions has access to affordable, quality health care coverage.

Today we have a choice: to keep the collapsing law that is Obamacare, or to start the process of fixing our broken health care system. This is a rescue mission: The American Health Care Act (AHCA) puts people back in charge of their health care, and for those worried about protections for pre-existing conditions, our plan ensures access to affordable, quality coverage. Read about the AHCA and my personal commitment to protecting people with pre-existing conditions here:

Today is historic. With the American Health Care Act, the House voted to keep its promise to the American people: we’re going to repeal Obamacare and replace it with a health care system that puts them — not the federal government — in control of their health care decisions.
To me, protecting people with preexisting conditions isn’t just good policy — it’s a personal mission.

Today I’m introducing the Steve Gleason Enduring Voices Act to give a voice to the voiceless. Steve Gleason is a hero and inspiration to all of us, and especially to the thousands of Americans living with degenerative diseases who, like him, rely on speech generating devices to communicate with their family, friends, and doctors. When bureaucratic rules threatened to silence many of them, the Gleason Act gave these individuals the peace of mind to know that their voices will continue to be heard. The Steve Gleason Enduring Voices Act ensures there are “no white flags” and that access to speech generating devices continues permanently for those who need it most. #NoWhiteFlags Team Gleason

In 2014, Gail Gleason, a mother from Spokane, came to me with a great idea. Gail and her son, Steve, feared thousands of people would lose their ability to communicate with the world around them – to share their stories, order coffee, tell jokes, ask for help, or say “I love you”. Today, I’m proud to introduce the Steve Gleason Enduring Voices Act to help make permanent changes to Medicare to allow those with ALS and other diseases the opportunity to access speech generating devices.

Hydropower plays a major role in our economy and energy supply in Eastern Washington. It is clean, safe, reliable, renewable, and affordable. That’s why yesterday, I introduced the Hydropower Regulatory Modernization Act of 2017 to modernize and streamline hydropower relicensing processes. On average, it takes only 18 months to license a new natural gas facility, but it can take up to 10 years or longer to license a new hydropower project or relicense an existing facility. As the largest source of renewable energy in the United States, we need to modernize the way we license and relicense hydropower and this legislation will do that.

Currently, the physician-to-population ratio in rural communities is stark. Only about 10 percent of physicians practice in these areas, even though almost a quarter of the population lives there. Compared to doctors who train in the traditional Medicare program, those trained at Teaching Health Centers are 82 percent more likely to practice primary care, 20 percent more likely to work in rural communities, and 55 percent more likely to work in underserved areas.

The Columbia River Treaty plays an important role in helping meet our energy needs in the Pacific Northwest. I want to renegotiate it so it can continue to benefit people in Eastern Washington for years to come.

Hydropower produces 70 percent of our energy in Washington State and is the largest source of clean, renewable, reliable, and affordable energy in the country. That’s why I introduced the Hydropower Regulatory Modernization Act of 2017. In the words of ClearPath Action, this bill will improve private-sector hydropower growth “by creating a more reasonable licensing process that balances clean energy development with environmental concerns.”
The WOTUS rule targets our rural communities and makes it more and more difficult for hardworking Americans to be successful. Thank you to the Trump Administration for taking action.

Making sure we safely dispose of nuclear waste isn't just good policy--it's a commitment we’ve made as a country. This is especially true for the Hanford site here in Washington. This morning, I met with Nancy Voorhees, Interim Executive Director of the Spokane Teaching Health Clinic, and other representatives from teaching health centers (THCs) across the country to discuss my legislation to reauthorize the Teaching Health Center and Graduate Medical Education (THCGME) program nationwide. It’s estimated that we will have a nationwide doctor shortage of 23,000 by 2025. This shortage will especially impact rural communities like those here in Eastern Washington. That’s where THCs come in. They provide residencies here in our community, and those trained in Eastern Washington are more likely to stay in Eastern Washington. Those educated at THCs are also 82 percent more likely to practice primary care, 20 percent more likely to work in rural communities, and 55 percent more likely to work in underserved communities. This program can help meet our doctor shortage here in the Inland Northwest and provide us more doctors for our rural and underserved communities. Learn more about my bill here: https://mcmorris.house.gov/teachinghealthcenters/

As Rosh Hashanah approaches, I want to wish my Jewish friends in Eastern Washington and throughout the country a sweet and happy New Year.   This past year has been one filled with conflict and divisiveness at home and around the world. Yet, it has also been a time of hope, with Israel enjoying a tenuous peace with her neighbors and a new administration fervently devoted to defending the Jewish state.   I just returned last month from my third trip to Israel, leading a senior congressional delegation, meeting with the Prime Minister and defense officials. Each time I return, I am impressed anew with how the hard work and innovative genius of modern Israelis has turned the ancient Holy Land into a world leader in defense, software, agriculture, and medicine.   At a time when so many issues divide us, it is a hopeful sign that support for Israel continues to enjoy bipartisan support. Indeed, resolutions condemning Iranian aggressiveness have been adopted by almost unanimous votes.   Yet 5778 brings, as every new year does, new energy for us to meet the challenges in the year ahead.   As you know, it is a flavorful custom to eat apples dipped in honey to celebrate Rosh Hashanah. Since Washington state produces almost half the apples grown in the United States, I think we can see that in synagogues and homes across the nation, our fruit will be sweetening the lives of millions of Jewish families -- which is fitting, since Jewish culture and tradition has enriched the lives of all Americans for so long.  On Rosh Hashanah it is written and on Yom Kippur it is sealed. May it be written and may it be sealed that you have a new year that brings fulfillment and happiness, peace and prosperity - all of life’s very best things. Have a Happy, Healthy New Year! Shanah Tovah!

Under the current status quo of our tax code, the wealthy, the well-connected, and the big corporations are who benefit most. Through special interest loopholes and tax breaks, they take advantage of our complicated tax code. They can afford to pay the best and brightest accountants to get them the best deal. That’s not fairness.   What we want to do is level the playing field for everyone. We want to cut out those special interest loopholes and make the tax code simpler-- so simple you could file your taxes on a postcard. We want to bring down rates for the middle class so you can keep more of your hard-earned dollars. We want to double the standard deduction so if you’re single, your first $12,000 is tax-free, and if you’re married, it’s your first $24,000. We want to give small businesses tax relief so they can expand and create jobs. Our plan will benefit everyone. Learn more here:

As I think of all the natural disasters and the national tragedies, I find myself just wanting to share a message with everyone in this country. I am reminded just how important it is how we treat each other. As basic as the Golden Rule -- to do unto others as you would have them do unto you. To seek understanding in a way that helps support each other, and that happens both in times of need and celebration.   Too often today, we put labels on people. We cast them aside, or worse, we attack them, whether it’s their creed, their skin color, their religion, their political views. Let’s pray as a nation that each one of us can be an ambassador of peace. We are in this together as Americans, and I challenge everyone to go have coffee with someone they don’t agree with. Listen to them. Invite your neighbors in for dinner. Put the smartphone away. Be open to new ideas. We are all part of the moral fabric that holds our country together and let’s make sure we’re a part of making it strong.

Today we introduced the Tax Cuts and Jobs Act, our plan to reform our broken tax code. This legislation will take us from 7 brackets to 5, keeping the top bracket at the same level. It will nearly double the standard deduction, increase the Child Tax Credit, and keep the Earned Income Tax Bracket. It makes no changes to 401k or IRA accounts so Americans can continue to save for the future. It also lowers the corporate tax rate from 35%, the highest in the industrialized world, to 20% to keep more jobs here in America. It also supports small business by lowering rates to the lowest since World War II. Learn more:

I joined Fox Business earlier today to talk more about the Tax Cuts and Jobs Act. This bill will lower tax rates for the low and middle class. To put it in perspective, the average family will save $1182 a year under our plan.

In the Northwest, we get roughly 70 percent of our energy from hydropower. This week, my legislation, the Hydropower Policy Modernization Act, will come up for a vote. My bill will streamline hydropower relicensing process and officially classify existing hydropower as a clean, renewable energy resource. Did you know that on average in the U.S. it takes only 18 months to license a new natural gas facility but can take up to 10 years or longer to license a new hydropower project or relicense an existing facility. My bill will help change that.

Yesterday, the House voted to go to conference committee on the tax bill where we will work out the differences between our bill and the Senate’s. Recently, I’ve heard from people in Eastern Washington about the need to protect graduate student tuition waivers and the tax exempt status of Private Activity Bonds used to fund the construction of low-income housing. That’s why I’m working to make sure both of these issues are fixed during the conference committee process. These are priorities for me and I’m optimistic that we can get these changes reflected in the final bill that we send to the President’s desk.

Did you know that roughly 70% of the population takes the standard deduction when filing their taxes? Our plan will double that standard deduction for everyone. That means that if you’re a single person, it goes from $6,000 to $12,000 and if you’re married, from $12,000 to $24,000. That is a direct tax benefit to many families here in Eastern Washington. Throughout the debate on the Tax Cuts & Jobs Act, many claimed the bill would trigger automatic cuts to Medicare, Medicaid, and Social Security. I reassured people that we would not allow those cuts to take place. Today, the House voted to waive statutory PAYGO requirements, which means there will be no cuts to any of these programs as a result of the Tax Cuts & Jobs Act, just like we promised.
